lings, and that envision a playful and passionate approach to sexuality as part of a rich and fulfilling life.How to Be Queer starts with Homer’s Iliad and moves through lyric poetry, tragedy, comedy, philosophy, and biography, drawing on a wide range of authors, including Sappho, Plato, Anacreon, Pindar, Theognis, Aristophanes, and Xenophon. It features both beautiful poetry and thought-provoking prose, emotional outpourings and humorous anecdotes. From Homer’s story of the relationship between Achilles and Patroclus, one of the most intense between men in world literature, to Sappho’s lyrics on the pleasures and pains of loving women, these writings show the many meanings of what the Greeks called eros.Complete with brief introductions to the selections, and with the original Greek on facing pages, How to Be Queer reveals what the Greeks knew long ago—that the erotic and queer are a source of life and a cause for celebration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aClassical literature. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aHomosexualityzGreece. 0aHomosexualityzRome. 0aSex customszGreece. 0aSex customszRome. 0aSex in literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAccount.  aAchaeans.  aAchilles.  aAgamemnon.  aAgathon.  aAlcibiades.  aAutolycus.  aBattle.  aBeauty.  aBoys.  aCallias.  aCentury.  aChild.  aCleinias.  aCritoboulus.  aDeath.  aDesire.  aDivine.  aEarth.  aEros.  aFriends.  aGaze.  aGrace.  aGreek.  aGrief.  aHades.  aHair.  aHeart.  aHeracles.  aHippothales.  aHorse.  aHuman.  aKtesippus.  aLeader.  aLest.  aLive.  aLost.  aLove.  aLysis.  aMoney.  aMother.  aNature.  aNoble.  aOffers.  aPatroclus.  aPeleus.  aPerson.  aPhaedrus.  aPlato.  aPoet.  aPoetry.  aPower.